All through 2020, Dadaab refugees have seen little effort at developing durable solutions.Refugees in Dadaab need access to opportunities and the possibility to choose how they want to live.  I first met Bahati Ernestine, 26, in Nairobi late 2019, when in-person events were still the norm. Her story offered a rare light in what was yet another jargon-studded conference to seek solutions for hundreds of thousands of refugees stuck in remote camps in Kenya.
Among the world’s mere three per cent refugees to have completed university education, Bahati had surmounted immeasurable odds to earn a nursing degree.



