Escaping genocide in Rwanda, in 1994, Bahati’s family had first fled to the Democratic Republic of Congo, from where they eventually made their way to Kenya. On arriving in Kenya, her parents decided against settling in a refugee camp, opting instead to make a living on the outskirts of Nairobi.
That decision proved life-changing for Bahati, opening access to education opportunities she may not have had in a camp. She had the courage and determination to persevere, snapping up whatever meagre opportunity that presented itself — from a scholarship programme to an internship at the renowned Kenyatta National Hospital.





Along the way, she faced challenges — that those without a country to call home often do: convincing the bureaucracy that you exist, fighting to be more than a refugee. No birth certificate and limited rights meant this remained a constant struggle.
I’ve spent the last two years closely following the waning hopes of Dadaab refugees; their three-decade ordeal for human dignity remains elusive, locked up as they are in remote camps.
Therefore, stumbling upon Bahati provided hope and inspiration. Yet Bahati’s personal struggle and resilience — formidable given the odds stacked against her — was made possible by choice and opportunities, however limited.



