Catastrophic policy choice
But the over two-hundred thousand refugees in Dadaab, consigned to a barren prison, have never had much choice — except to go back to the country they fled from. For a majority, that happens to be Somalia, where skills needed to evade threat to life are as elemental as skills required to not go hungry.
It all stems from a catastrophic policy choice: to keep refugees in camps, where they remain dependent on measly and ever-dwindling humanitarian assistance, with virtually no access to jobs, higher education or specialised healthcare.
Lifesaving to start with, when their existence stretches for decades, camps become terribly inhumane, testing human resilience, grinding hopes and crushing talent of people, who could otherwise contribute so much to society.
It was this realisation, two years ago, that prompted States to agree to a Global Compact on Refugees (GCR). The compact conceived assisting refugees as a global public responsibility, requiring increased support for hosting countries to ensure they could provide refugees access to public services and assimilate them in their social fabric. Many rich countries also recognised the need for additional efforts to provide resettlement options for refugees.



