And at the first-ever Global Refugee Forum 2019, the countries in the region under the auspices of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development pledged to establish a ‘Support Platform’, which could mobilise funding to help host countries such as Kenya implement the commitments they have taken when subscribing to the GCR.
The Covid-19 pandemic has slashed that progress. All through 2020, Dadaab refugees have seen little effort at developing durable solutions respecting their dignity and legitimate aspiration to have a life, rather than just survive and resettlement options have all but waned, with UNHCR announcing 2020 to be a record low for resettlement.
So, the ‘city of thorns’ remains, where lives continue to be on hold, and dreams die a slow death.
Critical challenge
The withering hopes of successive generations is taking a severe psychological toll on many. As we warned, a mental health crisis is growing in Dadaab. Already this year, at least 13 people have attempted suicide in Dagahaley camp, two with fatal outcomes.



